Message: What is the difference between target CPA and Max Conversion?

Hi Steve, great question! Target CPA (Cost-Per-Acquisition) is an automated bidding strategy where you set a specific cost target for each conversion. Our Ad Manager will adjust your bids to achieve that target cost and deliver conversions. Max Conversions, on the other hand, focuses on spending your daily budget while optimizing to deliver as many conversions as possible. Both strategies utilize AI and machine learning to achieve conversions and require the integration of a pixel/postback. For more detailed information, you can check out this article: [How to choose a bidding strategy](https://help.newsbreak.com/hc/en-us/articles/21344263367053-How-to-choose-a-bidding-strategy).
which bid type is more friendly for performance

Hi Steve, for performance advertisers, both Target CPA and Max Conversions can be effective depending on your specific goals. If you want stable daily spending and are especially good for a goal CPA of less than $50, Max Conversions might be the better choice. However, if you have a strict CPA goal and are less strict on daily spending, Target CPA could be more suitable. You can also switch between these strategies based on your campaign's performance. For more details, check out this article: [How to choose a bidding strategy](https://help.newsbreak.com/hc/en-us/articles/21344263367053-How-to-choose-a-bidding-strategy).

Hi Steve, Target ROAS (Return on Ad Spend) helps advertisers automatically adjust their bids to hit a specific revenue goal for every dollar spent on ads. This strategy is good for listicle-advertisers and optimizes conversions for different values for your business. If a Target ROAS ad set is not spending its budget, you might want to switch to Max Conversion Value to improve performance with a proper initial daily budget. For more detailed information, you can check out this article: [Newsbreak Ads Overview](https://help.newsbreak.com/hc/en-us/articles/21344263367053-How-to-choose-a-bidding-strategy).
